pr_title: Combine and publish results from parallel workflows
pr_body:
This PR extends the functionality of #792 and partially addresses #783.

After this PR, the workflow will:
* Push figures to `auto_generated_figures` branch
* Push workflow status to `workflow_testing_indicator` branch
* Automatically create a [dashboard](https://github.com/probml/pyprobml/blob/workflow_testing_indicator/README.md) containing the status of the workflow.

Steps:
- [x] Push status, logs, and figures to 20 different branches e.g. `auto_generated_figures_x`, where `x` varies from 0 to 19.
- [x] In the last step, clone the branches and combine the status, logs, and figures into a single folder. Push those single folders to corresponding single branches e.g. `auto_generated_figures`.
- [x] Autogenerate [dashboard](https://github.com/probml/pyprobml/blob/workflow_testing_indicator/README.md) to keep a track of failing notebooks.

## Description
Updated the code that generates figure 4.10 to avoid the confusion between likelihood and prior/posterior range.

### Figure Number
book1 - 4.10

### Figures
[gist](https://gist.github.com/patel-zeel/1fa7056535d872f5545e92c33bb1abf6)

### Issue 
#683 

## Steps

- [x] Updated the code following the PEP 8 guidelines.
- [x] Replaced `numpy` with `jax.numpy` following the [CONTRIBUTING.md](https://github.com/probml/pyprobml/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md) guidelines.
- [x] Using `exp -> sum -> logpmf` instead of `prod -> pmf` to avoid numerical underflow.

## Checklist:

- [x] Performed a self-review of the code
- [x] Tested on Google Colab.

## Potential problems/Important remarks

I have modified the colors and line styles to make plots visually separable when they superimpose. Please let me know if this is violating rules for using specific colors and styles for likelihood, prior and posterior.

pr_body:
## Description

Converted py files to notebooks.

### Issue 

#739
#740

## Steps

* Converted scripts at `scripts` folder to chapter-wise notebooks in `notebooks/book1` folder using [this](https://github.com/patel-zeel/pyprobml/blob/nb_convert_book1/notebooks/py_to_notebook_book1.ipynb) notebook.
* Moved existing notebooks to corresponding chapter-wise folders.
* Automatically converted the imports to `try: module except: %pip install module` pattern. Code to do this is in the [same notebook](https://github.com/patel-zeel/pyprobml/blob/nb_convert_book1/notebooks/py_to_notebook_book1.ipynb).
* Automatically redirect duplicate notebooks to their unique copy. for examples, check [this](https://github.com/patel-zeel/pyprobml/blob/nb_convert_book1/notebooks/book1/11/huberLossPlot.ipynb) and [this](https://github.com/patel-zeel/pyprobml/blob/nb_convert_book1/notebooks/book1/13/activation_fun_plot.ipynb).
* Automatically saving workflow status in `workflow_testing_indicator` from where it reflects in the "workflow" column of #739 and #740. This enables live monitoring the workflow status from this PR onwards. The notebook that generated automatic markdown table string from using `pandas` dataframes is located [here](https://github.com/patel-zeel/pyprobml/blob/nb_convert_book1/misc/auto_generate_issue.ipynb).
* Automatically push error log in `workflow_testing_indicator`. It can be laborious to look at the entire workflow error log to find out an error in a particular notebook so I am showing the logs for failed notebooks in the third column of #739 and #740. This is achieved by modifying `tests/test_notebooks.py` and `.github/notebooks.yml` files.
* Enabled `FIG_DIR` and `LATEXIFY` options. New instructions to use them will be available [here](https://github.com/probml/pyprobml/blob/master/notebooks/README.md).
* Replaced several `../figures` to `figures` to facilitate workflow execution.

## Potential problems/Important remarks
* Workflow fails for several notebooks due to various reasons (mostly due to broken APIs of python modules). This needs to be handled on a case-by-case basis. To easily do this, contributors should make use of the workflow status columns of #739 and #740.
* Workflow execution time-out is set at 10 minutes per notebook (which is huge). We should identify time taking notebooks and reduce their running time for workflows, for example, if a model is trained for 100 iterations, we can run it for 1-2 iterations inside the workflow by checking `WORKFLOW` environment variable.

pr_title: Combine and publish results from parallel workflows
pr_body:
This PR extends the functionality of #792 and partially addresses #783.

After this PR, the workflow will:
* Push figures to `auto_generated_figures` branch
* Push workflow status to `workflow_testing_indicator` branch
* Automatically create a [dashboard](https://github.com/probml/pyprobml/blob/workflow_testing_indicator/README.md) containing the status of the workflow.

Steps:
- [x] Push status, logs, and figures to 20 different branches e.g. `auto_generated_figures_x`, where `x` varies from 0 to 19.
- [x] In the last step, clone the branches and combine the status, logs, and figures into a single folder. Push those single folders to corresponding single branches e.g. `auto_generated_figures`.
- [x] Autogenerate [dashboard](https://github.com/probml/pyprobml/blob/workflow_testing_indicator/README.md) to keep a track of failing notebooks.
